Message forms display a two-button confirmation dialog.

```ts
const result = await Forms.message(player, options);
```

---

### Options

| Property | Type | Required | Description |
|----------|------|----------|------------|
| `title` | `FormText` | No | Dialog title |
| `body` | `FormText` | No | Message body |
| `button1` | `{ text: FormText }` | **Yes** | First button |
| `button2` | `{ text: FormText }` | **Yes** | Second button |
| `actions` | `[Function, Function]` | No | Callback tuple for each button |
| `onSelect` | `Function` | No | Global handler receiving `0` or `1` |

---

### Basic Example

```ts
await Forms.message(player, {
  title: "Delete World",
  body: "Are you sure? This cannot be undone.",
  button1: { text: "Delete" },
  button2: { text: "Cancel" },
  actions: [
    (p) => deleteWorld(p),
    (p) => p.sendMessage("Cancelled.")
  ]
});
```

---

### Result Data

| Value | Meaning |
|-------|--------|
| `0` | button1 was pressed |
| `1` | button2 was pressed |

```ts
const result = await Forms.message(player, options);

if (!result.canceled) {
  if (result.data === 0) {
    // button1 pressed
  } else {
    // button2 pressed
  }
}
```

> [!warning] Validation requires both `button1` and `button2` to be defined. Omitting either will fail in strict mode.

Modal forms display input controls and return typed values.

```ts
const result = await Forms.modal(player, options);
```

---

### Options

| Property | Type | Required | Description |
|----------|------|----------|------------|
| `title` | `FormText` | No | Form title |
| `submitButton` | `FormText` | No | Text on submit button |
| `controls` | `ModalControl[]` | **Yes** | Input controls and layout elements |
| `onSubmit` | `Function` | No | Called with all values on submit |
| `actions` | `ModalActionMap` | No | Per-control callbacks |

---

### Control Types

| Type | Output | Properties |
|------|--------|------------|
| `textField` | `string` | `label`, `placeholder?`, `defaultValue?`, `tooltip?` |
| `slider` | `number` | `label`, `min`, `max`, `step?`, `defaultValue?`, `tooltip?` |
| `toggle` | `boolean` | `label`, `defaultValue?`, `tooltip?` |
| `dropdown` | `number` | `label`, `options[]`, `defaultValueIndex?`, `tooltip?` |
| `header` | — | `text` (layout only, no value) |
| `label` | — | `text` (layout only, no value) |
| `divider` | — | (layout only, no value) |

---

### Full Example

```ts
const result = await Forms.modal(player, {
  title: "Player Settings",
  submitButton: "Save",
  controls: [
    { type: "header", text: "Display" },
    { type: "textField", label: "Nickname", placeholder: "Enter name..." },
    { type: "slider", label: "FOV", min: 60, max: 120, step: 5, defaultValue: 90 },
    { type: "divider" },
    { type: "header", text: "Gameplay" },
    { type: "toggle", label: "PvP Enabled", defaultValue: true },
    { type: "dropdown", label: "Difficulty", options: ["Easy", "Normal", "Hard"], defaultValueIndex: 1 }
  ],
  onSubmit: (values, player) => {
    // values is a typed tuple matching your controls
    const [nickname, fov, pvp, difficulty] = values;
    player.sendMessage(`Name: ${nickname}, FOV: ${fov}`);
  }
});
```

---

### Per-Control Actions

The `actions` map lets you run callbacks for individual controls by index:

```ts
await Forms.modal(player, {
  title: "Quick Settings",
  controls: [
    { type: "toggle", label: "Dark Mode" },
    { type: "slider", label: "Volume", min: 0, max: 100 }
  ] as const,
  actions: {
    0: (value, allValues, player) => {
      // value is boolean (from toggle)
      player.sendMessage(`Dark mode: ${value}`);
    },
    1: (value, allValues, player) => {
      // value is number (from slider)
      setVolume(value);
    }
  }
});
```

> [!tip] Use `as const` on your controls array for full type inference — TypeScript will infer the exact value types for each callback.

> [!info] Layout controls (`header`, `label`, `divider`) don't produce values — they're skipped in the values tuple. Only input controls (`textField`, `slider`, `toggle`, `dropdown`) contribute to the output.

The `FormPresets` class provides factory methods for common form patterns.

```ts
import { FormPresets, Forms } from "./API/FORMS";
```

---

### Available Presets

| Preset | Returns | Description |
|--------|---------|------------|
| `confirm()` | `MessageFormOptions` | Yes/No confirmation dialog |
| `dangerConfirm()` | `MessageFormOptions` | Destructive action confirmation |
| `ok()` | `ActionFormOptions` | Single-button notice |
| `error()` | `ActionFormOptions` | Error message with Close button |
| `success()` | `ActionFormOptions` | Success message with Nice button |
| `loading()` | `ActionFormOptions` | Loading indicator with label |

---

### Signatures

```ts
FormPresets.confirm(title?, body?, yes?, no?)
FormPresets.dangerConfirm(body?, title?)
FormPresets.ok(title?, body?, button?)
FormPresets.error(body?, title?)
FormPresets.success(body?, title?)
FormPresets.loading(title?, body?)
```

---

### Usage Examples

```ts
// Quick confirmation
await Forms.message(player, FormPresets.confirm());

// Custom confirm
await Forms.message(player, 
  FormPresets.confirm("Save?", "Save your progress?", "Save", "Don't Save")
);

// Danger confirmation
await Forms.message(player,
  FormPresets.dangerConfirm("This will delete all warps.")
);

// Error display
await Forms.action(player, 
  FormPresets.error("Failed to connect to server.")
);

// Success display
await Forms.action(player, 
  FormPresets.success("Warp created successfully!")
);
```

> [!tip] All preset parameters have sensible defaults — call them with no arguments for the standard behavior, or customize any parameter.

Forms+ uses a structured error hierarchy.

---

### Error Classes

All errors extend `FormsError`, which extends `Error`.

| Class | Code | When |
|-------|------|------|
| `FormsError` | `FORMS_ERROR` | Base error class |
| `InvalidPlayerError` | `INVALID_PLAYER` | Player is null, undefined, or invalid |
| `ValidationError` | `VALIDATION_ERROR` | Form options failed validation (strict mode) |
| `FormDisplayError` | `FORM_DISPLAY_ERROR` | Max retries exceeded |
| `FormCallbackError` | `FORM_CALLBACK_ERROR` | Exception thrown inside a callback |

---

### Error Properties

Every `FormsError` includes:

```ts
{
  name: string,     // e.g. "ValidationError"
  message: string,  // human-readable description
  code: string,     // machine-readable code
  details?: unknown // additional context (e.g. ValidationResult)
}
```

---

### Catching Errors

```ts
import { FormsError, ValidationError, FormCallbackError } from "./API/FORMS";

try {
  await Forms.action(player, options);
} catch (e) {
  if (e instanceof ValidationError) {
    console.warn("Validation:", e.details);
  } else if (e instanceof FormCallbackError) {
    console.warn("Callback crashed:", e.details);
  } else if (e instanceof FormsError) {
    console.warn(`[${e.code}] ${e.message}`);
  }
}
```

---

### Safe Callbacks

Forms+ wraps all user callbacks (actions, onSelect, onSubmit) in a `safe()` wrapper. If your callback throws, it's caught and re-thrown as a `FormCallbackError` with the original error in `details`.

> [!warning] In strict mode, invalid forms throw `ValidationError` immediately — the form is never shown. In non-strict mode, no error is thrown; the result simply returns `{ canceled: true, reason: "validation_failed" }`.

### Multi-Page Menu

```ts
async function mainMenu(player: Player) {
  await Forms.action(player, {
    title: "Main Menu",
    items: [
      { kind: "button", text: "Settings" },
      { kind: "button", text: "Warps" },
      { kind: "button", text: "Help" }
    ],
    actions: [
      (p) => settingsMenu(p),
      (p) => warpsMenu(p),
      (p) => helpMenu(p)
    ]
  });
}
```

---

### Confirm Before Action

```ts
const result = await Forms.message(player,
  FormPresets.dangerConfirm("Delete all warps?")
);

if (!result.canceled && result.data === 0) {
  deleteAllWarps();
}
```

---

### Settings Form with Defaults

```ts
function settingsForm(current: { name: string; volume: number; pvp: boolean }) {
  return FormBuilder.modal()
    .title("Settings")
    .textField("Name", "Enter name", current.name)
    .slider("Volume", 0, 100, 5, current.volume)
    .toggle("PvP", current.pvp)
    .onSubmit((values, player) => {
      const [name, volume, pvp] = values;
      saveSettings(player, { name, volume, pvp });
    })
    .build();
}
```

---

### Error-Safe Form Chain

```ts
try {
  const r1 = await Forms.action(player, menuForm);
  if (r1.canceled) return;

  const r2 = await Forms.message(player, confirmForm);
  if (r2.canceled || r2.data !== 0) return;

  const r3 = await Forms.modal(player, inputForm);
  if (r3.canceled) return;

  processData(r3.data);
} catch (e) {
  await Forms.action(player, FormPresets.error("Something went wrong."));
}
```

---

### Dynamic Button List

```ts
const players = world.getAllPlayers();

await Forms.action(player, {
  title: "Select Player",
  items: players.map(p => ({ kind: "button" as const, text: p.name })),
  onSelect: (index, player) => {
    const target = players[index];
    player.sendMessage(`Selected: ${target.name}`);
  }
});
```

> [!tip] These patterns cover the most common real-world use cases. Combine them to build complex multi-step UI flows.
